        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/16532",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Of course the mentioned problem is not the only one for encryption.\nSeveral other things have to be thought of when the Zend Framework should be able to be encrypted.\n\n",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-09-03T04:00:19.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-09-03T04:00:19.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/16533",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=nico",
                        "name": "nico",
                        "displayName": "Nico Edtinger",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "You mean it is not possible to use unencrypted files from the include path with zend guard? Otherwise it does not make sense to encrypt something that is open source anyway. Also this should be reported to the zend guard team. They could i.e. keep hashes of the original class names to support this use case. It is used quite often in autoloaders.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=nico",
                        "name": "nico",
                        "displayName": "Nico Edtinger",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-09-03T07:32:28.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-09-03T07:32:28.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/16552",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "No this is not what I meant...\n\nIn my company we use the Zend Framework for customer applications.\nFor us it's easier to encrypt all code... our source and also the ZF.\n\nAnd using the ZF encrypted did not work when obfuscation was turned on (which is mandatory because of security). The code mentioned above did solve the issue...\n\nAnyway... because we often include the trunk and did not always want to integrate the changes we do not use Zend Guard anymore... we throwed it away (as also the respone from the support team did not really help).\n\nNow we are using ioncobe which has not the problems...\n\nSo for us this issue is solved.\n\nFor any other guys having this problem there are only 3 solutions...\n\n*) turn off obfuscation (security risk)\n*) include all ZF classes to the ignore list\n*) use ion cube",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-09-08T11:56:26.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-09-08T11:56:26.000+0000"
                },
